   Here is an alphabetical list of hard-core
cocaine addicts by state and the rate of addiction per 1,000 state
residents as estimated in a Senate Judiciary Committee report.
   A hard-core addict was described in the study as someone who
uses cocaine at least once a week.
   Alabama 22,000, 5.5; Alaska 3,700, 7.1; Arizona 43,000, 12.7;
Arkansas 8,400, 3.5; California 325,000, 11.8; Colorado 34,000,
10.4; Connecticut 24,000, 7.5; Delaware 2,700, 4.2; District of
Columbia 20,000, 32.9; Florida 93,000, 7.7; Georgia 48,000, 7.7;
Hawaii 9,400, 8.7;
   Idaho 3,100, 3.1; Illinois 142,000, 12.2; Indiana 14,000, 2.5;
Iowa 7,800, 2.8; Kansas 13,000, 5.4; Kentucky 13,500, 3.6;
Louisiana 29,000, 6.5; Maine 2,900, 2.5; Maryland 47,000, 10.3;
Massachusetts 30,000, 5.2; Michigan 61,000, 6.6; Minnesota 26,000,
6.1; Mississippi 6,300, 2.4;
   Missouri 46,000, 9.0; Montana 1,700, 2.1; Nebraska 7,900, 4.9;
Nevada 23,000, 22.4; New Hampshire 3,500, 3.3; New Jersey 66,000,
8.6; New Mexico 12,800, 8.5; New York 434,000, 24.4; North Carolina
40,000, 6.3; North Dakota 1,400, 2.1; Ohio 57,000, 5.3; Oklahoma
22,500, 6.9;
   Oregon 17,000, 6.4; Pennsylvania 81,000, 6.8; Rhode Island
3,900, 3.9; South Carolina 12,600, 3.7; South Dakota 800, 1.1;
Tennessee 23,000, 4.7; Texas 144,000, 8.6; Utah 6,500, 3.9; Vermont
1,200, 2.2; Virginia 53,000, 9.0; Washington 18,000, 4.0; West
Virginia 3,800, 2.0; Wisconsin 47,000, 9.9, Wyoming 1,300, 2.7.
